    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1978-10-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1978-10-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="126"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d126">
                <head>126. Memorandum for the Record<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d126fn1"
                        >Source: Central Intelligence Agency, Office of the Director of Central
                        Intelligence, Job 81B00112R: Subject Files, Box 16, Folder 36: (<gloss
                            target="#t_SCC_1">SCC</gloss>) Nicaragua. Secret. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_BR_6">Bowie</persName> on November 8.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <idno type="document-identifier">NFAC–4995–78</idno>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1978-10-31">October 31, 1978</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_PRC_1">PRC</gloss> Meeting on Nicaragua, 31 October
                        1978</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">Zbigniew Brzezinski</persName>; <persName
                            corresp="#p_AD_1">David Aaron</persName>; <persName corresp="#p_PR_1"
                            >Robert Pastor</persName>, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss>;
                            <persName corresp="#p_CW_1">Warren Christopher</persName>; <persName
                            corresp="#p_VVPP_1">Viron Vaky</persName>; <persName corresp="#p_GBH_1"
                            >Brandon Grove</persName>, State Department; <persName corresp="#p_BR_6"
                            >Robert Bowie</persName>; [<hi rend="italic">name not declassified</hi>]
                            <gloss target="#t_CIA_1">CIA</gloss>; <persName corresp="#p_SWY_1"
                            >William Smith</persName>, <gloss target="#t_JCS_1">JCS</gloss>; two
                        others unknown to me</item>
                </list>
                <p>1. <persName corresp="#p_CW_1">Christopher</persName> explained that the
                    mediation efforts in Nicaragua had done well in getting the Broad Opposition
                    Front (<gloss target="#t_FAO_1">FAO</gloss>) to produce a responsible plan for
                    transition from the <persName corresp="#p_SDA_1">Somoza</persName> regime to a
                    successor government. Events were proceeding well, but several factors
                    jeopardized the mediation and required that the US now weigh in heavily to
                    persuade <persName corresp="#p_SDA_1">Somoza</persName> that his early
                    retirement (before 1979) from power is essential. These factors included <gloss
                        target="#t_FAO_1">FAO</gloss> fragility, impending <gloss target="#t_FSLN_1"
                        >FSLN</gloss> guerrilla attacks, and <persName corresp="#p_SDA_1"
                        >Somoza</persName>’s intention of publicly rejecting the plan on 3
                    November.</p>
                <pb facs="0387" n="336" xml:id="pg_336"/>
                <p>2. State recommended that the approach to <persName corresp="#p_SDA_1"
                        >Somoza</persName> be made immediately and in two stages: (1) <persName
                        corresp="#p_SDA_1">Somoza</persName> would be told on 1 November that the
                        <gloss target="#t_IMF_1">IMF</gloss> would be delaying its expected decision
                    on $20 million in compensatory drawing for at least two weeks, the US would
                    publicly announce that it was holding up all bilateral assistance and <gloss
                        target="#t_AID_1">AID</gloss> disbursements, and <persName
                        corresp="#p_SDA_1">Somoza</persName> would be nudged to accept the <gloss
                        target="#t_FAO_1">FAO</gloss> plan. (2) If, as expected, <persName
                        corresp="#p_SDA_1">Somoza</persName> rejects the <gloss target="#t_FAO_1"
                        >FAO</gloss> plan, he would be told that the US favors his early resignation
                    and would begin to take steps to withdraw support (US milgroup, <gloss
                        target="#t_AID_1">AID</gloss> mission, embassy personnel) and weigh in with
                        <persName corresp="#p_SDA_1">Somoza</persName>’s sources of arms (Israel,
                    Guatemala, etc.) and finances.</p>
                <p>3. Following some discussion, <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1">Brzezinski</persName>
                    argued that the decision to take these latter steps should be made only by the
                        <gloss target="#t_PRC_1">PRC</gloss> principals and, in any event, could be
                    delayed for a couple of weeks. He wanted other Latin American governments
                    involved. He was concerned that the National Guard might disintegrate when
                        <persName corresp="#p_SDA_1">Somoza</persName> left and that the <gloss
                        target="#t_FAO_1">FAO</gloss> would be too weak to rule.</p>
                <p>4. <persName corresp="#p_VVPP_1">Vaky</persName> discussed the problems inherent
                    in delay, but the bulk of opinion supported <persName corresp="#p_BZ_1"
                        >Brzezinski</persName>. There was then general agreement to implement step
                    one immediately and save step two for awhile, perhaps until it could be
                    considered by a meeting of the <gloss target="#t_PRC_1">PRC</gloss>
                    principals.</p>
                <p>5. <persName corresp="#p_AD_1">Aaron</persName> suggested that the US ought to be
                    sounding out the National Guard now in order to assure that it would adjust to
                        <persName corresp="#p_SDA_1">Somoza</persName>’s departure in an orderly
                    manner.</p>
            </div>
